==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Huckster
<hw>Huck"ster</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hukstere</ets>, <ets>hukster</ets>, OD. <ets>heukster</ets>, D.
<ets>heuker</ets>; akin to D. <ets>huiken</ets> to stoop, bend, OD.
<ets>huycken</ets>, <ets>huken</ets>, G. <ets>hocken</ets>, to squat,
Icel. <ets>h<?/ka</ets>; -- the peddler being named from his stooping
under the load on his back. Cf. <er>Hawk</er> to offer for sale.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A retailer of small articles, of provisions, and the
like; a peddler; a hawker.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mean, trickish fellow.</def> <rj><au>Bp.
Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Huckster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Huckster
<hw>Huck"ster</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Huckstered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Huckstering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To deal in small articles, or
in petty bargains.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hucksterage</ent>⟦br⟧
